We use as + adjective + as to compare things that are same:

You play tennis as well as I do.
(same ability)
My car is as expensive as yours.
(same cost)

We use not as+adjective+as (or not so+adjective+as) to compare two things that are diferent:

Mark isn't as/so intelligent as Susan.
(Susan is more intelligent)
New York City isn't as big as Mexico city.
(Mexico city is bigger)

And we use like to mean similar to or nearly the same as:

The English summer is like the Australian winter.
The Germans are not like the Italians.
